          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">It didn=E2=80=99t t=
ake long for some House members to conclude that the risks outweigh the rew=
ards of embracing the historic, headline-grabbing, fundraising-record-break=
ing <b>Harris</b> candidacy. Earlier today, six House Democrats resolutely =
distanced themselves from their party=E2=80=99s presumptive nominee and joi=
ned with the entire House Republican caucus to pass a 220-196 measure =E2=
=80=9Cstrongly condemning the Biden Administration and its Border Czar, Kam=
ala Harris=E2=80=99s, failure to secure the United States border.=E2=80=9D =
<br/><br/>The startling defection offers a window into the anxieties felt b=
y Democrats locked in close down-ballot races. Of the six members to sign t=
he measure, five are embattled so-called frontliners: <b>Don Davis</b> (Nor=
th Carolina), <b>Yadira Caraveo </b>(Colorado), <b>Jared Golden</b> (Maine)=
, <b>Mary Peltola </b>(Alaska), and <b>Marie
Gluesenkamp Perez</b> (Washington). The sixth member, Texas=E2=80=99s <b>He=
nry Cuellar</b>, represents a border district and could also be in electora=
l trouble. (Cuellar, if you recall, is currently under indictment, along wi=
th his wife, for allegedly accepting $600,000 in bribes from Azerbaijan.)<b=
r/><br/>At the moment, it remains unclear how Harris will play in certain d=
istricts versus others. The very, very early read on Harris is that she is =
performing better than <b>Biden</b> in national polling, but it will take a=
t least a week=E2=80=94if not longer=E2=80=94before benchmark polling of Ha=
rris in competitive districts comes back to candidates and incumbents. None=
theless, it=E2=80=99s both striking and telling that these Democratic membe=
rs chose to row upstream against the surge of enthusiasm and unprecedented =
fundraising. <br/><br/>When the House returns from August recess, these mem=
bers=E2=80=99 anxieties will likely be compounded by the annual September s=
pending battle ahead of the new fiscal year
on October 1, which brings with it the almost inevitable threat of a govern=
ment shutdown<i> deep </i>into election season. When I raised this topic wi=
th a senior Democratic aide on the Hill, they texted back, =E2=80=9Clol I d=
on=E2=80=99t think people have the brain capacity right now. We are tired.=
=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<i>Abby Livingston</i><br/> <br/><i>Okay, onto the main =
event=E2=80=A6</i><br/></td>
